<h3 xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" id="sites-page-title-header" style="" align="left">
<span id="sites-page-title" dir="ltr" tabindex="-1" style="outline: none">Chrome Security Reviews</span>
</h3>
<div id="sites-canvas-main" class="sites-canvas-main">
<div id="sites-canvas-main-content">
<table xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" cellspacing="0" class="sites-layout-name-one-column sites-layout-hbox"><tbody><tr><td class="sites-layout-tile sites-tile-name-content-1"><div dir="ltr"><font face="arial, sans-serif">
<div>
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><font face="arial, sans-serif"><span style="color:rgb(34,34,34);vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap">All launches and major changes to Chrome undergo a security review.</span></font></p>
<font face="arial, sans-serif">
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><br />
</p>
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><span style="color:rgb(34,34,34);font-weight:bold;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap">Please note that requesting a security review requires an @google.com account.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><br />
</p>
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><span style="color:rgb(34,34,34);vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap">The Chrome Security Team used to ask engineers and PMs to provide the same information over and over again for incremental launches. We also had a hard time keeping on top of incremental changes and we weren't really using the cumulative review data to give us insight into the ongoing engineering practices across Chrome.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><br />
</p>
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><span style="color:rgb(34,34,34);vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap">The process below aims on addressing these issues and making the review process simpler and faster for everyone.</span></p>
</font></div>
</font>
<h2><a name="TOC-How-does-the-security-review-process-work-"></a><span>How does the security review process work? </span></h2>
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">Simple!</span></p>
<font face="arial, sans-serif">
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><b style="font-weight:normal"><br />
</b></p>
<ol style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><li dir="ltr" style="list-style-type:decimal;font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><span style="font-style:normal;font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">Teams fill out a “team survey” ahead of time. </span><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">This survey captures your team’s engineering practices and project-specifics that are relevant to security. These living documents should be updated as engineering practices change on the team, though we’ll do our best to remind you to update your team survey ahead of time. This survey has engineering-focused questions and is best filled out by your TL, or even better, make some time and fill it in together as a team in a meeting.
</span><span style="font-weight:normal;line-height:1.15;white-space:pre-wrap">
<i>Note: For now team surveys are not required for Chrome OS sub-teams. Your team survey is being maintained by the Chrome OS security team. For more information, check out go/cros-security-review.</i></span></p>
</li>
</ol>
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><b style="font-weight:normal"><br />
</b></p>
<ol start="2" style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><li dir="ltr" style="list-style-type:decimal;font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">Per project or launch, fill out a short and streamlined “feature survey”. </span><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">These surveys are linked to your launch bug and should take 5-10 minutes to complete. They are short because most of the background information we need is stored in the Team survey. Please start the feature survey as early as conveniently possible (even if you just want security feedback in the design stage).</span></p>
</li>
</ol>
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><b style="font-weight:normal"><br />
</b></p>
<ol start="3" style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><li dir="ltr" style="list-style-type:decimal;font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">Sail through go/no-go meetings and sleep well knowing that the security team has your back.</span><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)"> We can flip security launch flags earlier having a comprehensive record and</span><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)"> </span><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">a better understanding of your projects and team practices. We can also keep you up to date on the number and severity of security bugs that we see and proactively reach out to the right people on your team.</span></p>
</li>
</ol>
</font>
<p dir="ltr" style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><br />
</p>
<h2><a name="TOC-FAQ"></a>FAQ</h2>
<h4><a name="TOC-Q:-Why-do-we-do-security-reviews-"></a>Q: Why do we do security reviews?</h4>
<font face="arial, sans-serif"><span style="line-height:1.15;white-space:pre-wrap;font-family:Arial,Verdana,sans-serif">Great question, and thanks for asking it! Security reviews serve three main purposes:</span></font><font face="arial, sans-serif">
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><b style="font-weight:normal"><br />
</b></p>
<ol style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><li dir="ltr" style="list-style-type:decimal;font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">Provides an opportunity to educate and advise on potential security issues</span><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">. Chrome is one of the hardest pieces of software in the world to secure: millions of lines of security-critical code, rendering untrusted content from all corners of the web, sitting on over 1 billion devices... that makes it an attractive target for the bad guys! Everyone in Chrome is responsible for security, and we're here to help point out and avoid security pitfalls.</span></p>
</li>
</ol>
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><b style="font-weight:normal"><br />
</b></p>
<ol start="2" style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><li dir="ltr" style="list-style-type:decimal;font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">It’s a second pair of (expert) eyes looking for security holes</span><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">.</span><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)"> </span><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">An attacker needs to only find one security bug in your project to exploit, while you have the job of defending your entire codebase. Not fair, right? We want an engineer on Chrome to look over your project with an eye on security, before someone with different motives takes a look when the project lands.</span></p>
</li>
</ol>
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><b style="font-weight:normal"><br />
</b></p>
<ol start="3" style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><li dir="ltr" style="list-style-type:decimal;font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:bold;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">Gives the security team an overview of what is happening in Chrome</span><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">. Good security advice is tailored to a team, but great security advice also considers the strategic direction of the entire product area. When we can keep tabs on developments and product trajectories across teams, it (hopefully) allows us to provide meaningful advice and recommendations, sometimes even before you approach us and ask for it!</span></p>
</li>
</ol>
</font>
<h4><a name="TOC-Q:-Is-there-anything-security-reviews-are-NOT-"></a><span>Q: Is there anything security reviews are NOT? </span></h4>
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)">Unfortunately, security reviews don’t mean that you can stop caring about security. Your team is still accountable and responsible for ensuring that your code is free of security bugs. Security reviews won’t catch all bugs, but they certainly do help to make sure your security practices are sound.</span></p>
<font face="arial, sans-serif">
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><br />
</p>
</font>
<h4><a name="TOC-Q:-Why-am-I-getting-pings-from-cluster-fuzz-on-launch-experiment-bugs-"></a>Q: Why am I getting pings from cluster-fuzz on launch/experiment bugs?</h4>
<p style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><span style="white-space:pre-wrap">New launch and experiment bugs are pinged once if no associated security survey is filed. You can prevent the issue from getting pinged by filing a security survey and adding the bug ID to the survey. The Security-Review-Pinged flag will also prevent future pings, and is added automatically when the issue is pinged.</span></p>
<font face="arial, sans-serif">
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><br />
</p>
</font>
<h4><a name="TOC-Q:-How-do-I-fill-out-a-team-survey-"></a><span style="vertical-align:baseline">Q: How do I fill out a team survey? </span></h4>
Team surveys can be completed at <a href="https://chrome-security-survey.appspot.com/">https://chrome-security-survey.appspot.com/</a>. Preferably, the TL for the team will complete the survey. Access is limited to those with @google.com accounts.
<h4><a name="TOC-Q:-How-do-I-fill-out-a-feature-survey-"></a><span style="vertical-align:baseline">Q: How do I fill out a feature survey?</span></h4>
You can complete a feature survey for every feature/project/launch by using the link on the launch bug that you file. If you want to get a head start before filing a launch bug or want a review on your feature, the feature survey is available anytime at <a href="https://chrome-security-survey.appspot.com/">https://chrome-security-survey.appspot.com/</a>.<font face="arial, sans-serif"><span style="line-height:1.15;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap"> </span><span style="line-height:14.9499998092651px;font-size:10pt;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:transparent">Access is limited to those with @google.com accounts.</span></font>
<p dir="ltr" style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><span style="vertical-align:baseline"><br />
</span></p>
<h4><a name="TOC-Q:-When-should-I-fill-out-a-feature-survey-"></a><span style="vertical-align:baseline">Q: When should I fill out a feature survey? </span></h4>
<div>
As early as possible, preferably right after you file a launch bug. The feature survey is available anytime at <a href="https://chrome-security-survey.appspot.com/">https://chrome-security-survey.appspot.com/</a>, and can be edited multiple times. Even if your design is not finalized, we track launch bugs and surveys and can provide feedback as soon as you file your survey.
<div><br />
</div>
<div><span>
<h4><a name="TOC-Q:-My-team-is-big.-How-can-I-find-out-if-we-ve-done-a-team-survey-already-"></a>Q: My team is big. How can I find out if we’ve done a team survey already? </h4>
<font face="arial, sans-serif"><span style="line-height:1.15;white-space:pre-wrap">When you fill out a project/launch survey you will see a list of all available team surveys. If you don’t see your team on there, you’re welcome to start filling it out. Just make sure to coordinate with your PM, TL, or whoever should be responsible for maintaining the survey.</span></font></span><span>
<p dir="ltr" style="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><br />
</p>
<h4><a name="TOC-Q:-What-are-the-access-controls-on-the-survey-Can-any-chromium.org-contributor-read-my-answers-"></a>Q: What are the access controls on the survey? Can any chromium.org contributor read my answers? </h4>
<font face="arial, sans-serif"><span style="line-height:1.15;white-space:pre-wrap;font-size:10pt;background-color:transparent">Only @google.com accounts can view and change the surveys. All changes are also being logged, so they can be reverted if necessary.</span></font></span><span><font face="arial, sans-serif">
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><br />
</p>
</font></span>
<h4><a name="TOC-Q:-Are-Chrome-and-Chrome-OS-using-the-same-security-review-process-"></a><span>Q: Are Chrome and Chrome OS using the same security review process? </span></h4>
<span>
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><span style="white-space:pre-wrap;line-height:1.15;font-family:arial,sans-serif">Yes, but with one important difference: for Chrome OS, the team survey has already been completed and is currently maintained by the Chrome OS security team (jorgelo@ is the main point of contact). To file a Chrome OS feature survey, please follow the steps at go/cros-security-review.</span></p>
<font face="arial, sans-serif">
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><br />
</p>
</font></span>
<h4><a name="TOC-Q:-I-have-other-questions.-How-can-I-get-in-contact-"></a><span>Q: I have other questions. How can I get in contact? </span></h4>
<span>
<p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.15;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt"><span style="font-size:13px;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre-wrap;background-color:rgb(255,255,255)"><font face="arial, sans-serif">The best address for us is security [at] chromium [dot] org, or if you’re a Googler you can reach us at</font></span><span style="font-family:arial,sans-serif;white-space:pre-wrap;line-height:1.15"> chrome-security [at] google [dot] com for Chrome stuff, chromeos-security [at] google [dot] com for Chrome OS stuff.</span></p>
</span></div>
</div>
</div></td></tr></tbody></table>
